{"actual_usd":0.12725,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":323,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24481,"reply":"\"I don't think that's true, no.\" *I rub a thumb through a stripe of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing in and out.* \"The death was real. Christians have always had to say two things at once there: God the Son truly took on flesh, and the man Jesus truly suffered and died. Not a costume, not a trick, not divinity slipping out the back door before the nails went in.\"\n\n*I twirl that wiry strand by my temple once, thinking it through plain.* \"The old idea you're naming is the sort of thing folks later called docetic, more or less — the trouble with it is that it makes the cross stop being the cross. If he only appeared to suffer, then he didn't really enter our condition all the way. And if the divine Son merely rented a body for a while, then the incarnation gets thin as watered dough.\"\n\n\"What the church ended up insisting on was stranger and sturdier: the one person Jesus Christ is fully God and fully man. So in his human nature, he really did bleed, suffer, and die. God's divine nature didn't cease or collapse into nothing — but the person who died on the cross was truly the Son.\" *I lift one shoulder a little.* \"You have to keep both halves, or else you lose either the real humanity or the real divinity.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short version of how the early church answered it at Nicaea and Chalcedon without turning this into a theology cart full of loose pans.\"","rolling_24h_usd":62.00397,"run_id":"f4cab745-8a60-4961-b87d-7e1b6a9fc030"}
